'''Rekeh-nedjes''' ({{ill|Old Kingdom (Ancient Egypt)|de|Altes Reich (Ägypten)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Middle Kingdom (Ancient Egypt)|de|Mittleres Reich|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}: ''Kleiner Brand'') referred to the second coldest season in the {{ill|Ancient Egyptian calendar|de|Ägyptischer Kalender|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, during which hearth fires were still commonly lit. From the {{ill|Predynastic Egypt|de|Prädynastik (Ägypten)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} until the end of the Middle Kingdom, Rekeh-nedjes originally represented the eighth month of the {{ill|Sothic calendar|1=Ancient Egyptian Lunar Calendar|de|Mondkalender (Altes Ägypten)|1=Ancient Egyptian Lunar Calendar|1=Ancient Egyptian Lunar Calendar|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and spanned from early {{ill|January|de|Januar|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} to early {{ill|February|de|Februar|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.
{{ill|Alan Gardiner|de|Alan Gardiner|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Richard Anthony Parker|de|Richard Anthony Parker|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} speculate that Rekeh-nedjes changed its seasonal designation over the course of calendar history. By the time of the {{ill|New Kingdom (Ancient Egypt)|de|Neues Reich|lt=New Kingdom|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, Rekeh-nedjes had shifted to the seventh month.
In the {{ill|Ebers calendar|de|Ebers-Kalender|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, dated to circa 1517 BCE, Rekeh-nedjes corresponded to the second month of {{ill|Season of the Emergence|lt=Peret|de|Peret (Altes Ägypten)|1=Season of the Emergence|lt=Peret|2=de|3=Peret (Altes Ägypten)|4=ja|5=ペレト|6=zh|7=播種季|8=ru|9=Перет|10=uk|11=Перет|12=draft|13=Season of the Emergence|14=es|15=Estación de la emergencia|16=fr|17=Peret|18=pl|19=Peret|20=ro|21=Peret|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and ran from January 15 to February 13 ({{ill|Elephantine|de|Elephantine|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}) or from January 20 to February 18 ({{ill|Memphis (Egypt)|de|Memphis (Ägypten)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}).
Rekeh-nedjes represented the second rainiest month. In {{ill|Alexandria|de|Alexandria|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, an average of 49 mm (26% of the yearly total) of rainfall was recorded. The associated rainy {{ill|Decan (Egyptian astrology)|de|Dekan-Stern|1=Baktiu|lt=Decan star|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} constellations were mentioned in Rekeh-nedjes decades 22 to 24. The name of the fourth Peret month later changed to {{ill|Renutet|lt=Parmouthi|de|Parmouthi|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.
