{{Infobox hieroglyphs |NAME = <hiero>r:k-V28 n-D:s</hiero> |NAME-TRANSKRIPTION = ''Rkḥ-nds'' |NAME-ERKLÄRUNG = ''Kleiner Brand'' |NAME2 = <hiero>N11:Z1*Z1*Z1*Z1 pr-D21:X1</hiero> |NAME2-TRANSKRIPTION =''prt'' |NAME2-ERKLÄRUNG = ''Vierter Monat der Periode [[:en:Season of the Emergence|Peret]]'' }}
'''Rekeh-nedjes''' ({{ill|Old Kingdom (Ancient Egypt)|de|Altes Reich (Ägypten)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Old Kingdom (Ancient Egypt)|qq=}} and [[:en:Middle Kingdom of Egypt|Middle Kingdom (Ancient Egypt)]]: ''Kleiner Brand'') referred to the second coldest season in the [[:en:Egyptian calendar|Ancient Egyptian calendar]], during which hearth fires were still commonly lit. From the {{ill|Predynastic Egypt|de|Prädynastik (Ägypten)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Predynastic Egypt|qq=}} until the end of the Middle Kingdom, Rekeh-nedjes originally represented the eighth month of the {{ill|Sothic calendar|1=Ancient Egyptian Lunar Calendar|de|Mondkalender (Altes Ägypten)|1=Ancient Egyptian Lunar Calendar|1=Ancient Egyptian Lunar Calendar|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sothic calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/Ancient Egyptian Lunar Calendar|qq=}} and spanned from early [[:en:January|January]] to early [[:en:February|February]].
[[:en:Alan Gardiner|Alan Gardiner]] and [[:en:Richard Anthony Parker|Richard Anthony Parker]] speculate that Rekeh-nedjes changed its seasonal designation over the course of calendar history. By the time of the [[:en:New Kingdom of Egypt|New Kingdom]], Rekeh-nedjes had shifted to the seventh month.
In the {{ill|Ebers calendar|de|Ebers-Kalender|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ebers calendar|qq=}}, dated to circa 1517 BCE, Rekeh-nedjes corresponded to the second month of [[:en:Season of the Emergence|Peret]] and ran from January 15 to February 13 ([[:en:Elephantine|Elephantine]]) or from January 20 to February 18 ([[:en:Memphis, Egypt|Memphis (Egypt)]]).
Rekeh-nedjes represented the second rainiest month. In [[:en:Alexandria|Alexandria]], an average of 49 mm (26% of the yearly total) of rainfall was recorded. The associated rainy {{ill|Decan (Egyptian astrology)|de|Dekan-Stern|1=Baktiu|lt=Decan star|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Decan (Egyptian astrology)|13=User:Immanuelle/Baktiu|qq=}} constellations were mentioned in Rekeh-nedjes decades 22 to 24. The name of the fourth Peret month later changed to {{ill|Renutet|lt=Parmouthi|de|Parmouthi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Renutet|qq=}}.
== Literature == * {{ill|Rolf Krauss|de|Rolf Krauss|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rolf Krauss|qq=}}: ''Sothis- und Monddaten: Studien zur astronomischen und technischen Chronologie Altägyptens.'' Gerstenberg, Hildesheim 1985, {{Falsche ISBN|3-8067-8086-X}}. * [[:en:Richard Anthony Parker|Richard Anthony Parker]]: ''The calendars of ancient Egypt.'' Chicago Press, Chicago 1950. * Heinz Schamp: ''Ägypten: Das alte Kulturland am Nil auf dem Weg in die Zukunft – Raum, Gesellschaft, Geschichte, Kultur, Wirtschaft.'' Erdmann, Tübingen 1977, ISBN 3-7711-0263-4, p. 26. * {{ill|Siegfried Schott|de|Siegfried Schott|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Siegfried Schott|qq=}}: ''Altägyptische Festdaten.'' Verlag der Akademie der Wissenschaften und der Literatur, Mainz/Wiesbaden 1950.
